Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Jianjie Wang

2023-03-10

My meme


I created this meme because my imagined college life didn’t match what I actually experienced. I’m not trying to say that college is bad or boring. Actually, I think college life is very fulfilling. But just because it’s full enough, it can lead to a lack of energy, which is the sleepiness shown in the picture.

library(magick)

#import first picture
excited <- image_read("excited.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(200)


#import second picture
tired <- image_read("tired.jfif")%>%
  image_scale(200)

#write text for first picture
before <- image_blank(width = 200,height = 113,color ="#FFF2F4" ) %>%
  image_annotate(gravity = "center", text = "Before \ngoing to \nuniversity", color = "#000000",size = 20)

#write text for second picture
after <- image_blank(width = 200 , height = 200, color = "#FFF2F4")%>%
  image_annotate(gravity = "center", text = "After \ngoing to \nuniversity", color = "#000000",size = 20)

#create top row
before_in <- c(excited, before)
top <- image_append(before_in)

#create bottom row
after_in <- c(tired,after)
bottom <- image_append(after_in)

#put them together
meme <- c(top,bottom)%>%
  #make text on the right of picture
  image_append(stack = TRUE)%>%
  #fix the size of meme
  image_scale(600)

#save meme as my_meme.png
image_write(meme,"my_meme.png")
meme

My animation


I created this gif because the process of rain is usually a long one, and most of us, either because of our work at hand or because of our environment, can’t watch a rain in peace. This gif uses a wide-angle lens so that we can see the movement of clouds in the sky, and we can also feel the environment changes in the rain through the imprint of raindrops on the lens. I hope this gif can give us a relatively objective view of a rain.

library(magick)

# create frames
# use function image_scale to change the size of picture
# use function image_crop to cut picture
rain1 <- image_read("1.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain2 <- image_read("2.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain3 <- image_read("3.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain4 <- image_read("4.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain5 <- image_read("5.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain6 <- image_read("6.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain7 <- image_read("7.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")
rain8 <- image_read("8.png")%>%
  image_scale(600)%>%
  image_crop("338x338+131")

#put frames together
frames <- c(rain1,rain2,rain3,rain4,rain5,rain6,rain7,rain8)

#create gif
animation <- image_animate(frames,fps = 2)

#save gif as my_animation
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
animation
